MEMORANDUM OF APPEAL
UNDER SECTION 415 BNSS (CORRESPONDING TO SECTION 374 CrPC)
AGAINST THE JUDGMENT DATED 15.01.2026 PASSED IN SPECIAL SESSION CASE NO. 1/2025

TO,
THE HON'BLE CHIEF JUSTICE AND HIS COMPANION JUSTICES
OF THE HON'BLE HIGH COURT OF RAJASTHAN AT JODHPUR.

THE HUMBLE APPEAL OF THE APPELLANT MOST RESPECTFULLY SHOWETH:

1. IMPUGNED JUDGMENT
1.1 The Appellant has been convicted by the learned Trial Court in connection with partial collapse of the outer wall of Maharana Pratap Stadium, Udaipur, on the allegation of negligent construction and defective mortar quality.
1.2 The conviction is primarily founded on a forensic report allegedly showing failure of strength/workability parameters.
1.3 The impugned judgment is contrary to settled criminal jurisprudence, technical standards, and mandatory sampling protocol safeguards, and is liable to be set aside.

2. SHORT FACTUAL BACKGROUND
2.1 The incident occurred during severe rain/storm conditions.
2.2 Sampling was allegedly done in adverse weather, without proper sealing records, without contractor representative presence, and without full chain-of-custody documentation.
2.3 The prosecution relied on a testing approach unsuitable for hardened masonry material.

3. SUBSTANTIAL GROUNDS OF APPEAL

GROUND A: FSL METHODOLOGY IS TECHNICALLY INAPPLICABLE
3.1 The prosecution's forensic reasoning is vitiated because the reported test approach uses fresh-concrete oriented standards against old/hardened wall material.
3.2 IS 1199:2018 is for sampling/workability context of fresh concrete and not for retrospective hardened masonry-mortar failure attribution.
3.3 Hardened masonry material analysis requires standards aligned with masonry/hardened examination protocols (including IS 2250 framework and ASTM hardened-mortar analytical methodology, subject to formal proof at trial record level).
3.4 Conviction based on a foundationally mismatched test standard is unsafe in criminal law.

GROUND B: CHAIN OF CUSTODY BREAK - EVIDENTIARY RELIABILITY LOST
3.5 There is no complete, tamper-safe chain from site collection to laboratory receipt with sealed continuity, handler log, and independent attestation.
3.6 Absence of robust chain integrity destroys evidentiary confidence in forensic conclusions.
3.7 Criminal conviction cannot stand where the core scientific exhibit lacks assured continuity and authenticity.

GROUND C: MANDATORY PROCEDURAL SAFEGUARDS NOT FOLLOWED
3.8 Sampling was not transparently documented with full panchnama quality, geo/time traceability, and adversarial fairness safeguards.
3.9 The contractor side was not meaningfully associated at critical sampling/sealing points as required for fair forensic process.
3.10 Such breach causes serious prejudice and violates principles of natural justice and fair trial.

GROUND D: NON-REPRESENTATIVE AND WEATHER-CONTAMINATED SAMPLING
3.11 Prosecution did not establish representative sampling methodology across structurally relevant points.
3.12 Rain/storm-time exposure and surface contamination risk were not excluded before sample interpretation.
3.13 Without establishing sample integrity and representativeness, inferential guilt is speculative.

GROUND E: CAUSATION NOT PROVED BEYOND REASONABLE DOUBT
3.14 Criminal negligence requires a clear causal nexus between the accused's specific act/omission and the incident.
3.15 The impugned judgment assumes causation from a disputed forensic base instead of proving it independently through reliable structural and contextual evidence.
3.16 Where severe weather and maintenance/supervision factors are not excluded, conviction cannot be sustained.

GROUND F: MISREADING OF DEFENCE EVIDENCE
3.17 The Trial Court did not adequately evaluate defence materials on protocol deviation, standards mismatch, and forensic unreliability.
3.18 Material contradictions in prosecution narrative were either ignored or treated as minor, despite going to the root of admissibility and reliability.

GROUND G: BENEFIT OF DOUBT ERRONEOUSLY DENIED
3.19 The prosecution evidence suffers from technical, procedural, and causal uncertainty.
3.20 In criminal law, these are not curable defects; they require acquittal/setting aside of conviction.

GROUND H: SENTENCE UNSUSTAINABLE IN LAW AND FACT
3.21 Once conviction foundation is unsafe, sentence automatically falls.
3.22 Even otherwise, sentence is excessive in light of evidentiary infirmities and mitigating circumstances on record.

4. GROUNDS FOR INTERIM RELIEF (SUSPENSION OF SENTENCE / BAIL)
4.1 Appeal raises substantial and arguable questions.
4.2 Core prosecution evidence is legally vulnerable due to standards mismatch and chain-of-custody defects.
4.3 Continued incarceration during pendency would cause irreparable prejudice.
4.4 Appellant undertakes to comply with all conditions imposed by this Hon'ble Court.

5. VERIFIED-CITATION COMPLIANCE NOTE (ARTEMIS-II)
5.1 The following authorities/standards are used as issue-signposts and must be treated as per verification tier in filing workflow:
    - VERIFIED: Section 374 CrPC equivalent appellate framework under BNSS mapping used in platform.
    - SECONDARY: Specific standards interplay references pending certified record annexure tagging.
    - PENDING: Any precedent name/para not accompanied by certified source annexure in the filing packet.
5.2 No `PENDING` authority should be projected as final before physical filing.

6. PRAYER
In light of the above, it is most respectfully prayed that this Hon'ble Court may be pleased to:

(i) Call for the records of Special Session Case No. 1/2025;
(ii) Admit and allow the present appeal;
(iii) Set aside the judgment of conviction dated 15.01.2026 and all consequential orders;
(iv) Acquit the Appellant of the charges, or in the alternative remand for fresh consideration after excluding legally inadmissible forensic foundation;
(v) Suspend sentence and enlarge the Appellant on bail during pendency of appeal;
(vi) Pass any other order deemed fit in the interest of justice.

AND FOR THIS ACT OF KINDNESS, THE APPELLANT SHALL EVER PRAY.

